 :tx/rationale "SIGMOID SOFT MEMBERSHIP: Replace the hard cutoff (sim >= threshold -> binary in/out) with a sigmoid gradient. A hard cutoff claims infinite confidence in the threshold value. A sigmoid says 'my confidence in the boundary has finite precision, so membership near the boundary is uncertain.' Formulation: membership_strength = sigmoid((sim - threshold) / temperature) where sigmoid(x) = 1/(1+exp(-x)). At temperature -> 0, this recovers the hard cutoff. At temperature=0.05, observations at threshold +/- 0.05 get partial membership (0.27-0.73). The existing update_centroid_weighted already supports weighted membership via the surprise_weight factor — multiply by membership_strength. The temperature parameter is ITSELF a calibratable parameter under ADR-FOUNDATION-031. It encodes how much we trust the threshold — high confidence -> low temperature -> sharp boundary. The initial temperature should be derived from the observed standard deviation of cosine similarities: temperature = stddev(cosines) / 2. This makes the sigmoid width proportional to the actual spread of the data. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031, INV-EMBEDDING-004, OBSERVER-6."
